**Three communication primitives:**

```rust
// 1. Request/Reply вҖ” synchronous (from agent's perspective)
//    Agent A asks Agent B a question and blocks until response
let response = bus.request(
    to: AgentId("agent-b"),
    payload: json!({ "type": "review", "file": "src/main.rs", "diff": "..." }),
    timeout: Duration::from_secs(120),
).await?;

// 2. Fire-and-forget вҖ” async notification
//    Agent A tells siblings about something, doesn't wait
bus.send(
    to: AgentId("agent-b"),
    payload: json!({ "type": "file_changed", "path": "src/lib.rs" }),
).await?;

// 3. Broadcast вҖ” pub/sub within namespace
//    Agent A announces to all siblings + parent
bus.broadcast(
    topic: "progress",
    payload: json!({ "phase": "testing", "percent": 75 }),
).await?;
```

### 6.2 Dynamic Team Composition

**The primary agent gets a `spawn` tool exposed via its MCP socket.** This is how it autonomously builds teams:

```json
// Tools available to the primary agent via MCP
{
  "tools": [
    {
      "name": "forge_spawn_agent",
      "description": "Spawn a sub-agent with a specific profile and task",
      "input_schema": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "profile": { "type": "string", "description": "Nix agent profile name" },
          "task": { "type": "string", "description": "What this agent should do" },
          "wait": { "type": "boolean", "description": "Block until agent completes" }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "forge_message_agent",
      "description": "Send a message to another agent and optionally wait for reply",
      "input_schema": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "agent_id": { "type": "string" },
          "payload": { "type": "object" },
          "wait_reply": { "type": "boolean" },
          "timeout_secs": { "type": "integer" }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "forge_list_agents",
      "description": "List all agents in your namespace with their status"
    },
    {
      "name": "forge_kill_agent",
      "description": "Terminate a child agent",
      "input_schema": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "agent_id": { "type": "string" },
          "reason": { "type": "string" }
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

**Example: Primary agent dynamically composes a team:**

```
Primary Agent (profile: "orchestrator")
в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ [Reads spec, decides it needs 3 parallel implementers + 1 reviewer]
в”Ӯ
в”ңв”Җв”Җ forge_spawn_agent(profile: "implementer", task: "Implement auth module")
в”Ӯ   вҶ’ Agent A spawned (auto-approved, within soft cap)
в”Ӯ
в”ңв”Җв”Җ forge_spawn_agent(profile: "implementer", task: "Implement API routes")
в”Ӯ   вҶ’ Agent B spawned (auto-approved)
в”Ӯ
в”ңв”Җв”Җ forge_spawn_agent(profile: "implementer", task: "Implement database layer")
в”Ӯ   вҶ’ Agent C spawned (auto-approved)
в”Ӯ
в”ңв”Җв”Җ forge_spawn_agent(profile: "security-reviewer", task: "Review all changes when implementers complete")
в”Ӯ   вҶ’ Agent D spawned (auto-approved)
в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ [Agents A, B, C work in parallel on shared workspace]
в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ Agent A completes вҶ’ broadcasts("progress", { "module": "auth", "status": "done" })
в”Ӯ Agent B completes вҶ’ broadcasts("progress", { "module": "api", "status": "done" })
в”Ӯ Agent C has a question вҶ’ request(to: Agent A, { "type": "question", "about": "auth token format" })
в”Ӯ   Agent A replies вҶ’ { "format": "JWT", "schema": "..." }
в”Ӯ Agent C completes
в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ [Primary sees all 3 done via broadcast, messages reviewer]
в”Ӯ
в”ңв”Җв”Җ forge_message_agent(agent_id: D, payload: { "type": "start_review" }, wait_reply: true)
в”Ӯ   вҶ’ Agent D reviews all changes, replies with findings
в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ [Primary reads findings, decides Agent C's work needs fixes]
в”Ӯ
в”ңв”Җв”Җ forge_spawn_agent(profile: "implementer", task: "Fix issues in database layer: ...")
в”Ӯ   вҶ’ Agent E spawned (5th agent вҖ” still under soft cap)
в”Ӯ
в”ңв”Җв”Җ forge_spawn_agent(profile: "implementer", task: "Add integration tests")
в”Ӯ   вҶ’ Agent F вҖ” 6th agent, exceeds require-approval-after=5
в”Ӯ   вҶ’ APPROVAL GATE: daemon sends ApprovalRequest to Primary
в”Ӯ   вҶ’ Primary approves (via forge_approve_spawn tool)
в”Ӯ   вҶ’ Agent F spawned
```

### 6.3 Workspace Coordination

Multiple agents sharing a workspace need coordination to avoid conflicts:

**File-level locking via the daemon:**

```rust
// Exposed as MCP tool to agents
{
    "name": "forge_lock_files",
    "description": "Acquire exclusive lock on files before modifying",
    "input_schema": {
        "properties": {
            "paths": { "type": "array", "items": { "type": "string" } },
            "timeout_secs": { "type": "integer" }
        }
    }
}
```

```rust
// Daemon-side lock manager
struct WorkspaceLockManager {
    locks: DashMap<PathBuf, FileLock>,
}

struct FileLock {
    holder: AgentId,
    acquired_at: Instant,
    paths: Vec<PathBuf>,
}
```

**Strategies by workspace pattern:**

| Pattern | How It Works | When To Use |
|---------|-------------|-------------|
| **Shared workspace + file locks** | All agents see same filesystem, lock before writing | Small teams, tightly coupled code |
| **Git worktree per agent** | Each agent gets its own worktree, merge at completion | Independent modules, parallel features |
| **Hybrid** | Shared read, worktree for write, daemon merges | Default recommendation |

**The hybrid model in practice:**

```
/workspace/repo/                    (shared, read-only bind mount to all agents)
/workspace/worktrees/
в”ңв”Җв”Җ agent-a/                        (git worktree, agent A read-write)
в”ңв”Җв”Җ agent-b/                        (git worktree, agent B read-write)
в””в”Җв”Җ agent-c/                        (git worktree, agent C read-write)
```

- Agents read from the shared repo (latest main)
- Agents write to their own worktree
- On completion, daemon merges worktree вҶ’ shared repo (or creates PR branch)
- Merge conflicts вҶ’ daemon notifies parent agent for resolution

### 6.4 Agent Discovery & Capability Advertisement

Agents can advertise capabilities so siblings can find the right agent to ask:

```rust
// On spawn, agent registers its capabilities with the bus
bus.advertise(capabilities: vec![
    Capability::new("code-review", "Can review Rust and TypeScript code"),
    Capability::new("security-audit", "Can run SAST/DAST scans"),
]);

// Another agent can discover by capability
let reviewers = bus.discover("code-review").await?;
// вҶ’ [AgentInfo { id: "agent-d", name: "security-reviewer", capabilities: [...] }]

// Then message the discovered agent
bus.request(to: reviewers[0].id, payload: review_request).await?;
```

This means the primary agent doesn't need to hardcode who does what вҖ” it can spawn generic agents and let them self-organize based on advertised capabilities.

Does this inter-agent communication and team composition model look right?

